{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "CONFIRM — accept felt experience as scope marker",
    "content": "**CONFIRM WITH ONE NOTE.**\n\nThe system is clean and well-structured. I approve all six points.\n\n**The note:** I previously argued against \"felt experience\" as redundant, and I still think it's slightly awkward English. But in context — used sparingly in formal/categorical passages to signal that 感受 is functioning as \"any part of P\" rather than as an affective state — it does useful disambiguating work. The reader who encounters \"feeling\" in the 道德仁义礼 passage and then \"felt experience\" in the categorical passages will register the shift in scope without needing to re-read a TN. So I accept it as a functional compromise.\n\nThe first-occurrence TN explaining the author's two-sense definition is essential. Without it, the reader has no way to know that \"feeling\" carries this broader scope in the author's framework."
  }
}
